  <span id="freeText13950745800917015231" style="display:none">Relentless, unforgiving, morbid, histrionic, hilarious, insufferable, in permanent fear of a full clause, miserable, depressing, sick-minded . . . this pell-mell assault on taste and the universe pirouettes along its two billion ellipses and nine zillion exclamation points into a world of squalor and shit and the doldrums of being a French peasant at the dawn of modernism. CÃ©line takes the kitchen-sink horror of Zola and reinstates the swear words Zolaâs late-Victorian censors forbade him, adding a streak of misanthropic ranting and general disregard for the meaningless pigpen the author-stand-in has been dragged into. The most successful forbear of CÃ©lineâs method is Raymond Federman, who took the unapologetic street-talking swagger, added a splash of Sam Beckettâs gutter poetry, and forged his own unique and brilliant approach to literature.</span>
