<span id="freeTextContainer4719796049504944711">âAs soon as things begin to look up a little, all people can think of is piggishnessâ¦â<br/><b>Louis-Ferdinand CÃ©line</b> is a virtuoso of explicit narration, a prodigy of grotesque and a czar of cynicismâ¦<br/>ââYouâre working too hard! Youâre a sap! You think they appreciate it? â¦ If you knock yourself out, whoâs going to take care of you? Not your boss, I bet! Buy me a menthe, kid! â¦ Iâll sing you The Girl from Mostaganem â¦ Itâll drive you crazy, youâll see â¦â For that little number sheâd hike up her skirt fron</span>
  <span id="freeText4719796049504944711" style="display:none">âAs soon as things begin to look up a little, all people can think of is piggishnessâ¦â<br /><b>Louis-Ferdinand CÃ©line</b> is a virtuoso of explicit narration, a prodigy of grotesque and a czar of cynicismâ¦<br />ââYouâre working too hard! Youâre a sap! You think they appreciate it? â¦ If you knock yourself out, whoâs going to take care of you? Not your boss, I bet! Buy me a menthe, kid! â¦ Iâll sing you The Girl from Mostaganem â¦ Itâll drive you crazy, youâll see â¦â For that little number sheâd hike up her skirt front and back â¦ She didnât wear any panties, so it was a real belly dance â¦ Sheâd do it right out in the open â¦ in the middle of the Galerie â¦ The other floozies would come running â¦ usually with three or four customers each â¦ Bums, jerkoffs, bankrupt peepers â¦ âDo your stuff, Suzy! Donât piss crooked!â She sure threw her twot around â¦ You could see it bobbing up and down â¦ The crowd clapped and cheered, that Tunisian dance of hers was some excitement â¦ It always drew a crowd. When it was over, Iâd buy her her menthe â¦ Weâd all end up at the Insurrection â¦â<br />And this lacy passage is rather humble.<br />And when <b>Louis-Ferdinand CÃ©line</b> wishes to be especially vibrantly delirious he turns to surrealismâ¦<br />âWhen we got to the Arc de Triomphe, the whole crowd began to whirl like a merry-go-round. The whole mob was chasing Mireille. The square was littered with corpses. The living were tearing off each otherâs pricks. The Englishwoman was toting her car over her head at armâs length. Hurray, hurray! She knocks over a bus with it. The traffic is blocked by three files of Mobile Guards with shouldered rifles. All for our benefit. Mireilleâs dress flies away. The Englishwoman flings herself on the kid, claws at her breasts â¦ trickling, pouring, red all over. We fall, we writhe all together, we strangle each other. Pure bedlam.<br />The flame under the Arc de Triomphe rises, rises higher, breaks, scatters through the sky â¦ The whole place smells of smoked ham â¦ Then Mireille whispering in my ear, speaking to me at last: âFerdinand, my darling, I love you! â¦ I admit it, you have wonderful ideas!â The flames rain down on us, everyone picks up a big chunk â¦ We stuff them sizzling and whirling into our flies. The ladies put on bouquets of fire â¦ We fall asleep inside each other.<br />Twenty-five thousand policemen clear the Place de la Concorde. It was too much for us inside each other. It was too hot. There was smoke coming out. It was hell.â<br />On being born we buy our death on credit and every month we pay on accounts and keep fearing the end of paymentsâ¦ And death lies in wait.</span>
  <a data-text-id="4719796049504944711" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


