<span id="freeTextContainer14936441560039712422">While I very much liked <i>Death on The Installment Plan</i> I loved the shit out of <i>Journey To The End of Night</i>. I canât help compare the two, and while the latterâs better, the former/sequel is very good.<br/><br/><i>Death</i> focuses primarily on the author/characterâs (toss-up!) reflections on his formative years. After a brief tour of the present the narrator hustles back to his early childhood with his perenially frazzled shopowner parents. He later attends an English boarding school, cycles through shitty jobs, </span>
  <span id="freeText14936441560039712422" style="display:none">While I very much liked <i>Death on The Installment Plan</i> I loved the shit out of <i>Journey To The End of Night</i>. I canât help compare the two, and while the latterâs better, the former/sequel is very good.<br /><br /><i>Death</i> focuses primarily on the author/characterâs (toss-up!) reflections on his formative years. After a brief tour of the present the narrator hustles back to his early childhood with his perenially frazzled shopowner parents. He later attends an English boarding school, cycles through shitty jobs, moves in with uncle, becomes an inventorâs apprentice, and moves to the country with said inventor. Whereas Celine seemed to approach <i>Journey</i> guns-a-blazinâ, he seems to stall a bit, especially early on, with <i>Death</i>. Once he finds his rhythm, though, thereâs no one in Celineâs league for full-frontal, foot-stomping, literary rants. Heâs brilliantly in control when heâs out of control. His indignation, whether affected or authentic, is a thing of beauty. Iâm sure I missed socio-political elements inherent in <i>Death</i>.<br /><br /><i>Death</i> also runs significantly longer than its predecessor; the extra pages could wear a reader down. Still, Iâm comparing <i>Death</i> to one of my favorite books ever, and while itâs not on my favorite books ever list, itâs still really fuckinâ good. But read <i>Journey</i> first. Itâs better.<br /></span>
